   {:e #blake3 "01fffda8c7dfcc7a6c18c7fdb4cc9b6cb7de569e47c5d64f5fdea064e8f7afa3" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "ACP DESIGN SESSION START: Action-Centric Projection is the unification of the output pipeline, guidance system, and budget management into a single algebraic structure. The key invariant: AT EVERY BUDGET LEVEL, THE AGENT CAN TAKE THE CORRECT NEXT ACTION. This is the compositional guarantee that dissolves the truncation problem. The action (R(t) recommendation) is structurally first and never truncated. Context fills around it in precedence order. Evidence is available on demand. The guidance footer disappears as a separate concept — the Action IS the primary output.; DEEP INSIGHT: The truncation problem is a SPEC-IMPLEMENTATION DIVERGENCE, not a bug fix. The spec (INV-BUDGET-006) says: 'The pipeline never produces output that is merely truncated — it always re-projects at a lower level.' But the implementation uses enforce_ceiling() which is exactly truncation. The projection pyramid (pi0-pi3) exists in spec but is not implemented in the output pipeline. Each command should have MULTI-LEVEL RENDERERS: status at pi0 (full dashboard), pi1 (coherence + tasks), pi2 (F(S) + next), pi3 (one-line). The budget gate should SELECT LEVEL not TRUNCATE TEXT. Additionally, the spec has status as CHEAP (50 tokens) which contradicts its role as the primary orientation command. The spec needs an ADR amendment: status -> MODERATE. The root cause: commands produce ONE string, the budget gate truncates it. The solution: commands produce MULTI-LEVEL projections, the budget gate selects the appropriate level.; CRYSTALLIZATION — ACP Spec Elements:\n\nINV-BUDGET-007 (Action-Centric Projection Completeness): At every budget level B >= MIN_OUTPUT, the projected output contains a complete, actionable recommendation. Formally: forall B >= 50: exists action A in project(store, B) such that A.command is executable and A.rationale is non-empty. The action is NEVER truncated — it occupies the structurally first position in the output. Falsification: Any budget level >= MIN_OUTPUT produces output without an executable action command.\n\nINV-BUDGET-008 (Context Fill Monotonicity): For budget B1 > B2, project(store, B1) contains all ContextBlocks present in project(store, B2) plus zero or more additional blocks. Context is ADDITIVE — increasing budget adds context, never replaces or reorders it. Formally: B1 > B2 implies context_blocks(B1) is superset of context_blocks(B2). Falsification: Increasing budget removes a context block that was present at lower budget.\n\nINV-BUDGET-009 (Guidance-Projection Unification): The guidance system R(t) and the output projection function share the same action computation. There is exactly ONE code path that determines the recommended action. The guidance footer is not a separate computation appended to command output — it IS the action layer of the projection. Falsification: The action in a command's output differs from the R(t) recommendation at the same store state, OR the guidance footer is computed by a different code path than the projection action.\n\nADR-BUDGET-005 (Action-Centric Over Content-Centric Projection): The output pipeline is organized around WHAT THE AGENT SHOULD DO (action-first) rather than WHAT THE STORE CONTAINS (content-first). This resolves the truncation-vs-information tension: the action is always complete, context scales with budget, evidence is on-demand. Alternative rejected: content-centric projection with pyramid summaries (solves compression but not activation — the agent still needs to extract the action from compressed content).\n\nADR-BUDGET-006 (Activation Density Over Information Density): Output quality is measured by activation density (correct-basin-activating tokens per context unit consumed) not information density (semantic units per token). A 10-token action 'braid go t-fd30' that activates the task-execution basin has higher activation density than a 50-token status summary that activates the observation basin. Implication: the projection function should optimize for activation, not compression.\n\nADR-BUDGET-007 (Four Activation Strategies for Four k* Regimes): High k* (>0.7) = Demonstrate (rich context, ~300 tokens). Medium k* (0.4-0.7) = Navigate (precise pointers, ~100 tokens). Low k* (0.2-0.4) = Imperative (action only, ~10-20 tokens). Critical k* (<0.2) = Signal (harvest, ~5 tokens). These map to the projection pyramid pi0-pi3 but are cognitively grounded in activation theory rather than ad-hoc token bands.; Session entity: :task/t-f2870405; Session entity: :task/t-6fc38f24; Session entity: :task/t-ad1ba61d; Session 027 first batch: 10 tasks closed. BOUNDARY-1 (BoundaryCheck trait + SetRelation + BoundaryDivergence + BoundaryEvaluation + BoundaryRegistry), BOUNDARY-2 (registry), BOUNDARY-IMPL-5 (SpecImplBoundary), BOUNDARY-DEFAULT (default_boundaries), BOUNDARY-COMPAT (golden F(S) test), task search, task list filtering, CRB-4 :tx/reconciled schema, CRB-7 knowledge_relevance_scan, CRB-10 :recon-source/* schema. 43 bilateral tests passing, 1343 total tests. Experience note: braid task search is immediately useful — found 34 topology tasks instantly. The knowledge_relevance_scan broadening from spec-only to spec+task+observation closes the meta-irony gap. The BoundaryCheck trait is the right abstraction — SpecImplBoundary wraps the existing bilateral scan with zero behavioral change while enabling new boundary types to be added with one register() call.; RADICAL INSIGHT — Action-Centric Projection (ACP): The truncation problem reveals a deeper architectural error. We're treating output as CONTENT to be compressed. But from the prompt-optimization perspective, output is ACTIVATION — a field configuration over the agent's latent manifold. The correct question isn't 'how do I fit this in fewer tokens?' but 'what is the MINIMAL field configuration that activates the correct reasoning basin?' The answer: THE ACTION. Every braid output should decompose into: (1) Action — what the agent should do next (NEVER truncated, ~10 tokens, the R(t) top recommendation), (2) Context — why this action is correct (scales with budget, precedence-ordered), (3) Evidence — full supporting data (available via follow-up query). This reframes the entire pyramid: levels aren't 'less detail' — they're different activation strategies for different k* regimes. At high k*: demonstrate (rich worked examples). At medium k*: navigate (precise pointers). At low k*: imperative (single command). At critical k*: signal (one bit). The deepest part: the guidance system IS the projection function. R(t) provides the Action. The budget system determines how much Context. They're the same operation, not competing concerns. This eliminates the truncation problem by construction — you can't truncate what's structurally first.\nSession entity: :task/t-c776bd2c; Session entity: :task/t-aa491def; Session entity: :task/t-5ff3684a; Session entity: :task/t-c32ef3c0; Session entity: :task/t-6819ac57; Session entity: :task/t-60954541; Session entity: :task/t-e7f78088; Session entity: :task/t-23a63f33; Session entity: :task/t-e0e989fc; Session entity: :task/t-81a5df5a; Session entity: :task/t-da41afef; Session entity: :task/t-7f5eef5e; Session entity: :task/t-de010208; Session entity: :task/t-9152305d" :op :assert}
